{
  "What is the name of our galaxy?": "",
  "Whirlpool": "",
  "Milky Way": "",
  "Triangulum": "",
  "Andromeda": "",
  "Our solar system is located in the Milky Way galaxy, a barred spiral galaxy containing hundreds of billions of stars.": "",
  "Which planet is closest to the Sun?": "",
  "Venus": "",
  "Mercury": "",
  "Mars": "",
  "Earth": "",
  "Mercury orbits at an average distance of about 58 million kilometers from the Sun, making it the closest planet in our solar system.": "",
  "What type of star is our Sun classified as?": "",
  "White dwarf under the given": "",
  "Yellow dwarf (G-type main-sequence)": "",
  "Red dwarf, particularly": "",
  "Blue giant, particularly": "",
  "The Sun is a G-type main-sequence star, often called a yellow dwarf, which means it fuses hydrogen into helium in its core and has a surface temperature of about 5,500 degrees Celsius.": "",
  "Approximately how old is the Earth?": "",
  "500 million years": "",
  "10 billion years": "",
  "4.6 billion years": "",
  "1.5 billion years": "",
  "Radiometric dating of meteorites and the oldest Earth rocks indicates that our planet formed approximately 4.6 billion years ago from the solar nebula.": "",
  "What force holds planets in orbit around the Sun?": "",
  "Gravitational force": "",
  "Magnetic force": "",
  "Nuclear force": "",
  "Electromagnetic force": "",
  "Gravity is the fundamental force that keeps planets in elliptical orbits around the Sun, as described by Newton's law of universal gravitation and refined by Einstein's general relativity.": "",
  "Earth is located in which arm of the Milky Way galaxy?": "",
  "Sagittarius Arm": "",
  "Perseus Arm": "",
  "Orion Arm (Orion Spur)": "",
  "Norma Arm": "",
  "Our solar system resides in the Orion Arm (also called the Orion Spur), a minor spiral arm located between the larger Perseus and Sagittarius arms of the Milky Way.": "",
  "How long does light from the Sun take to reach Earth?": "",
  "About 1 second": "",
  "About 1 hour": "",
  "About 8 minutes": "",
  "About 24 hours": "",
  "Sunlight travels at approximately 300,000 kilometers per second and covers the roughly 150 million kilometer distance to Earth in about 8 minutes and 20 seconds.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a terrestrial planet?": "",
  "Jupiter": "",
  "Jupiter is a gas giant, not a terrestrial planet. Terrestrial planets (Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars) have solid rocky surfaces, while gas giants are composed primarily of hydrogen and helium.": "",
  "What separates the inner planets from the outer planets in our solar system?": "",
  "The asteroid belt": "",
  "A ring of comets": "",
  "The Kuiper Belt": "",
  "The Oort Cloud": "",
  "The asteroid belt, located between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, marks the boundary between the four inner terrestrial planets and the four outer gas and ice giant planets.": "",
  "What evidence supports the Big Bang theory?": "",
  "The number of planets in our solar system": "",
  "The existence of black holes": "",
  "Cosmic microwave background radiation": "",
  "The distance between galaxies remaining constant": "",
  "The cosmic microwave background radiation, discovered in 1965, is a faint glow of microwave radiation filling the universe that represents the residual heat from the early expansion, providing strong evidence for the Big Bang theory.": "",
  "What is a light-year?": "",
  "The brightness of a star measured over one year": "",
  "The amount of energy the Sun produces in one year": "",
  "The distance light travels in one year": "",
  "The time it takes light to travel around Earth": "",
  "A light-year is a unit of distance equal to approximately 9.46 trillion kilometers, which is the distance that light travels through a vacuum in one calendar year.": "",
  "What is the astronomical unit (AU)?": "",
  "The distance from Earth to the Moon": "",
  "The distance light travels in one second": "",
  "The average distance from Earth to the Sun": "",
  "The diameter of our solar system": "",
  "An astronomical unit (AU) is defined as the average distance between the Earth and the Sun, approximately 150 million kilometers, and is commonly used to measure distances within our solar system.": "",
  "What is a nebula?": "",
  "A planet with no atmosphere": "",
  "A type of black hole": "",
  "A massive cloud of gas and dust in space": "",
  "A dying star that has collapsed": "",
  "A nebula is an enormous cloud of gas (primarily hydrogen and helium) and dust in interstellar space, and nebulae are often the birthplaces of new stars when regions of the cloud collapse under gravity.": "",
  "What is the solar nebula hypothesis?": "",
  "The theory that the Sun will eventually become a nebula": "",
  "The hypothesis that nebulae orbit the Sun": "",
  "The idea that the solar system formed from a rotating cloud of gas and dust": "",
  "The theory that planets were captured by the Sun's gravity": "",
  "The solar nebula hypothesis proposes that our solar system formed about 4.6 billion years ago from the gravitational collapse of a giant rotating cloud of gas and dust, with the Sun forming at the center and planets accreting from the remaining material.": "",
  "What does the term 'redshift' mean in astronomy?": "",
  "The color of the Sun at sunset": "",
  "The increase in wavelength of light from an object moving away from the observer": "",
  "A change in a star's brightness over time": "",
  "A star turning red as it cools down": "",
  "Redshift occurs when light from a distant object is stretched to longer (redder) wavelengths because the object is moving away from the observer, and it provides key evidence that the universe is expanding.": "",
  "What is a galaxy?": "",
  "A cluster of asteroids in deep space": "",
  "The space between two star systems": "",
  "A large system of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter bound together by gravity": "",
  "A single star system with orbiting planets": "",
  "A galaxy is a massive gravitationally bound system consisting of billions of stars, stellar remnants, interstellar gas, dust, and dark matter. Galaxies come in various shapes including spiral, elliptical, and irregular.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The absorption of radiation by atoms": "",
  "The combining of light atomic nuclei to form heavier ones, releasing energy": "",
  "The splitting of heavy atomic nuclei into lighter ones": "",
  "The decay of radioactive elements in space": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is the process by which lighter atomic nuclei combine to form heavier nuclei, releasing enormous amounts of energy. This is the process that powers the Sun and other stars, primarily fusing hydrogen into helium.": "",
  "What is the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram?": "",
  "A chart that plots stars by their luminosity versus surface temperature": "",
  "A map showing the positions of stars in our galaxy": "",
  "A diagram showing the orbits of planets": "",
  "A timeline of the universe's expansion": "",
  "The Hertzsprung-Russell (H-R) diagram is a scatter plot of stars showing the relationship between luminosity (or absolute magnitude) and surface temperature (or spectral type), which helps astronomers classify stars and understand stellar evolution.": "",
  "What does the term 'main sequence' mean in stellar astronomy?": "",
  "The sequence of planets from the Sun outward": "",
  "The path a star takes through the galaxy": "",
  "The stage in a star's life when it fuses hydrogen into helium in its core": "",
  "The order in which stars were discovered": "",
  "The main sequence refers to the continuous band of stars that appear on the H-R diagram, representing the longest and most stable phase of a star's life during which it fuses hydrogen into helium in its core.": "",
  "What is the cosmological principle?": "",
  "The idea that Earth is at the center of the universe": "",
  "The rule that all galaxies are spiral-shaped": "",
  "The principle that the universe has a definite edge": "",
  "The assumption that the universe is homogeneous and isotropic on large scales": "",
  "The cosmological principle states that on sufficiently large scales, the universe looks the same in all directions (isotropic) and from every location (homogeneous), meaning no place in the universe is fundamentally special.": "",
  "A student looks through a telescope and notices that a distant galaxy's light appears shifted toward the red end of the spectrum. What can the student conclude about this galaxy?": "",
  "The galaxy is moving toward Earth": "",
  "The galaxy is not moving at all": "",
  "The galaxy is about to explode": "",
  "The galaxy is moving away from Earth": "",
  "A redshift in a galaxy's light indicates that the galaxy is moving away from the observer, as the Doppler effect stretches the wavelengths of light to longer, redder wavelengths when the source recedes.": "",
  "NASA scientists discover a rocky planet orbiting a star 20 light-years away. The planet is roughly Earth-sized and located in the star's habitable zone. Why is the habitable zone significant for the search for life?": "",
  "It is the zone where temperatures allow liquid water to exist on a planet's surface": "",
  "It is the area where planets have the thickest atmospheres": "",
  "It is the region closest to the star where radiation is lowest": "",
  "It is where the strongest magnetic fields are found": "",
  "The habitable zone (also called the Goldilocks zone) is the range of orbital distances from a star where conditions are right for liquid water to exist on a planet's surface, which is considered essential for life as we know it.": "",
  "An astronomer observes that galaxies farther from Earth are moving away faster than closer galaxies. This observation supports which major scientific idea?": "",
  "The steady-state theory of the universe": "",
  "The theory of planetary migration": "",
  "Hubble's Law and the expansion of the universe": "",
  "The geocentric model": "",
  "Hubble's Law states that the recessional velocity of a galaxy is proportional to its distance from us, providing direct evidence that the universe is expanding uniformly in all directions.": "",
  "A geology student finds a meteorite and has it dated using radiometric methods. The result shows an age of 4.56 billion years. What does this tell scientists about the solar system?": "",
  "The solar system is older than the universe": "",
  "The meteorite was formed on Mars": "",
  "The meteorite was part of a comet": "",
  "It provides evidence for the age of the solar system": "",
  "Meteorites are some of the oldest and most primitive objects in the solar system. Their radiometric ages of approximately 4.56 billion years provide direct evidence for when the solar system formed from the solar nebula.": "",
  "During a planetarium visit, students learn that a star much more massive than the Sun will have a shorter lifespan. Why do more massive stars burn out faster?": "",
  "They have less hydrogen fuel to begin with": "",
  "They fuse their fuel at a much faster rate due to higher core temperatures": "",
  "Their gravity slows down nuclear reactions": "",
  "They lose mass to solar winds more quickly": "",
  "More massive stars have higher core temperatures and pressures, causing them to fuse hydrogen at an enormously faster rate. Although they have more fuel, they consume it so much faster that their lifespans are significantly shorter than less massive stars.": "",
  "A team of engineers is designing a space probe to travel to the outer solar system. They plan to use a gravity assist maneuver around Jupiter. What principle makes a gravity assist possible?": "",
  "Jupiter's magnetic field accelerates the probe": "",
  "The probe generates its own gravitational pull near Jupiter": "",
  "The probe uses Jupiter's gravitational field to gain speed and change direction": "",
  "The probe bounces off Jupiter's atmosphere": "",
  "A gravity assist (or slingshot maneuver) uses a planet's gravitational field and orbital velocity to accelerate a spacecraft and alter its trajectory, effectively transferring some of the planet's orbital energy to the probe without using fuel.": "",
  "Researchers detect a uniform faint glow of microwave radiation coming from all directions in the sky. A student asks what this radiation is. How should their teacher explain its significance?": "",
  "It is light reflected by the Moon": "",
  "It is the cosmic microwave background, the afterglow of the Big Bang": "",
  "It is radiation emitted by the Sun": "",
  "It is radio interference from cell towers on Earth": "",
  "The cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation is the remnant thermal radiation from when the universe cooled enough for atoms to form, about 380,000 years after the Big Bang. Its uniformity and slight temperature fluctuations strongly support the Big Bang theory.": "",
  "A student is comparing the composition of the Sun to that of Jupiter. Both are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium. Why did Jupiter not become a star like the Sun?": "",
  "Jupiter lacks helium in its core": "",
  "Jupiter does not have enough mass to generate the core temperatures needed for nuclear fusion": "",
  "Jupiter rotates too slowly to produce energy": "",
  "Jupiter is too far from the Sun to ignite": "",
  "Although Jupiter is composed mainly of hydrogen and helium like the Sun, it has only about 0.1% of the Sun's mass. Nuclear fusion requires extremely high core temperatures and pressures that only objects roughly 80 times Jupiter's mass can achieve.": "",
  "A space agency wants to search for potentially habitable exoplanets. They plan to use the transit method, which detects tiny dips in a star's brightness. What causes these brightness dips?": "",
  "A planet passes between the star and the observer, blocking some light": "",
  "The star's magnetic field fluctuates": "",
  "The star periodically dims on its own": "",
  "Asteroids collide with the star": "",
  "The transit method detects exoplanets by measuring the slight decrease in a star's brightness when a planet crosses (transits) in front of it from our point of view. The size and timing of the dip can reveal the planet's size and orbital period.": "",
  "A science class is building a scale model of the solar system in the school hallway. They discover that if the Sun is the size of a basketball, Earth would be smaller than a peppercorn and located about 26 meters away. What does this exercise demonstrate about the solar system?": "",
  "That all planets are roughly the same size": "",
  "That the Sun is only slightly larger than the planets": "",
  "That the solar system is mostly empty space with vast distances between objects": "",
  "That planets are much larger than they appear from Earth": "",
  "Scale models of the solar system vividly demonstrate that the solar system is overwhelmingly composed of empty space. Even at reduced scales, the distances between planets are enormous relative to the sizes of the objects themselves.": ""
}